bly of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]},{"name":"Thornton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from the very numerous places named with Old English <i>þorn</i> ‘thorn bush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The given name is associated with the American writer  Thornton Wilder  (  1897–1975 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Thornton Fitton was born in 1348, in Dutton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hammon Fitton, was 24 and her mother, Elizabeth THORNTON, was 21. She married Henry DUTTON in 1365, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1348–":"1348–Surnud","1345–1382":"1345–1382","1347–Male":"1347–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1344–1